<dl id="n12020d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12020d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12020d"> 20(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">D</font> reads his hand <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12020d"><li>FW 430.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n12020d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n12020d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12020d">MS BL 47483-112</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:178 <a name="qAd5" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qAd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd5.htm#n12020d">Draft: III&sect;2A.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A quelque temps de l&agrave;, une religieuse vint en visite au ch&acirc;teau. C&apos;&eacute;tait une juive convertie, tr&egrave;s consid&eacute;r&eacute;e pour son habilet&eacute; en m&eacute;decine et en chiromancie. Voyant Bertrand rel&eacute;gu&eacute; dans un coin, trait&eacute; de p&acirc;tre et de charretier par ses parents, elle lui dit: &ldquo;Mon enfant, que celui qui a souffert la passion vous b&eacute;nisse!&rdquo; Bertrand, croyant qu&apos;elle voulait se moquer de lui comme les autres, la mena&ccedil;a de la frapper. Mais la religieuse lui prit la main d&apos;un air compatissant, et, apr&egrave;s avoir longuement &eacute;tudi&eacute; les lignes de la paume, lui pr&eacute;dit qu&apos;il serait sage et heureux et que personne, dans le royaume de France, ne serait plus consid&eacute;r&eacute;. <br><font color="green">[In those days, a nun came to visit the castle. She was a jewish convert, famous for her knowledge of medicine and necromancy. When she saw Bertrand exiled in a corner, treated as a shepherd and wagoner by his parents, she told him: &lsquo;My child, he who has suffered the passion blesses you!&rsquo; Bertrand, who thought that like the others she wanted to mock him, threatened to hit her. But <mark>the nun took his hand with compassion, and, after having studied the lines in his hand carefully</mark>, she predicted that he would be wise and happy and that nobody, in the kingdom of France, would be more esteemed.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 176</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
